5113:174:   174	- 2026-04-26 [schema][scaffold-only-status] **New schema families should ship as scaffold-only stubs with `x-keeper-live-proof.status: "scaffold-only"` BEFORE any body is written, so consumers can pin the family name + version without false-claiming functionality.** Sprint 7h-12: 8 V2 families landed as scaffold-only — each has `const "<family>.v1"` for the `schema` key + `additionalProperties: false` so any manifest declaring the family today is rejected with a clean error pointing at the scaffold-only status. Beats two alternatives: (a) "land the family directory empty, no schema file" — consumers can't even pin the family, so versioning is ambiguous; (b) "land a permissive schema accepting `{}`" — silently passes validation today, fails at apply with a confusing "no provider" error. Scaffold-only is the explicit, self-documenting middle path. Pattern: any "we'll implement X later" announcement that ships a directory should also ship a stub with a const-locked identity + a `scaffold-only` annotation, never an empty file.
5119:380:   380	- 2026-04-26 [live-test][transcript-shape] **Live-test proof transcript MUST be machine-readable + schema-shaped + sanitized at write time, not committed-as-raw and triaged later.** `keeper_sdk/cli/_live/transcript.py` writes a fixed-shape JSON (`schema_family`, `schema_version`, `commander_pin`, `started_at`, `finished_at`, `phases[]`, `summary`) that `x-keeper-live-proof.evidence` consumes directly — no transformation step between live-run output and schema-graduation evidence. Sanitization is allowlist-based: `_SECRET_KEYS` (password/token/private_key/config/appKey/applicationKey/totp) get values replaced with literal `<redacted>`; UID-shaped strings (20-28 char URL-safe base64) get `_fingerprint`'d to `<uid:sha256-8>`. Post-write `secret_leak_check` greps for PEM blocks + raw env-var values + long unbroken hex runs as belt-and-braces. The CLI verb refuses to leave the file on disk if the leak check flags anything. Pattern: any "evidence" artefact that crosses the secret/public boundary needs (a) a fixed shape so consumers can parse without dialect, (b) write-time sanitization not post-hoc, and (c) a separate consistency check that doesn't share code with the sanitizer (different bug surface).
5120:399:   399	- 2026-04-26 [conventions-doc][reduces-task-body-overhead] **A single canonical CONVENTIONS doc inside the artifact directory it governs (here: `keeper_sdk/core/schemas/CONVENTIONS.md`) removes ~30% of per-task redundant context.** Before: every P*-impl task body re-derived `additionalProperties: false`, `x-keeper-live-proof` block shape, `$id` pattern, cross-family ref grammar, `uid_ref` semantic uniqueness pattern, `$comment` TODO marker convention, commit-message format. After: task body cites CONVENTIONS by path; worker reads it first; task body shrinks to the family-specific scope only. Workers propose amendments via DONE-dump LESSON CANDIDATE; parent integrates after 2+ families hit the same pattern (don't amend on a single-family quirk). Pattern: when 3+ artifact instances share 80%+ of their construction rules, factor the rules into a CONVENTIONS doc colocated with the artifacts. The doc becomes parent-owned; workers cite, don't edit.
5121:412:   412	- 2026-04-27 [daybook][regex-by-reference-inflation] **`pending_journal_items` regex (`agent_review_loop.py`: `^[-*]\s*\[\s\]` OR `"Pending decisions" in line`) double-counts every JOURNAL line that *references* the WORKTREES.md "Pending decisions" section, even when the referenced rows are DONE.** Sprint 7h-30 review fired sticky DAYBOOK alert (`pending_trend=[6,6,6]`) but 5 of 6 hits were historical sprint carry-over notes pointing at items 1-5 (closed in 7h-6); only 3 truly-open items remained in WORKTREES.md (#6 KSM live-proof, #7 bus.py cov, #8 cov ratchet 84→85). Fix applied in 7h-31: rephrase historical refs from `"Pending decisions"` (quoted) to `worktree-followups` (unquoted, regex-defanged) + `_[CLOSED 7h-6]_` suffix; pending count drops 6 → 0 honestly. Pattern: substring-match counters over append-only logs accumulate ghost-debt because closed items' textual references survive the closure event. Two structural mitigations: (A) regex requires line to start with checkbox or section header, not arbitrary in-line phrase, (B) close-out events rewrite the referenced phrase to a different token. Applied B for cheapness; A is the cleaner long-term fix in `agent_review_loop.py`.
5122:416:   416	- 2026-04-27 [capability-census][three-gates] **Treat schema status, provider slice, and live-proof transcript as three SEPARATE gates; only families with all three should claim "supported".** Sprint 7h-36 CDX-3 surfaced the canonical mismatch: `pam-environment.v1` had 2/3 gates green (provider apply works, transcript via smoke matrix), but missed the schema metadata gate (`x-keeper-live-proof` block absent at `pam-environment.v1.schema.json:1-8` while `CONVENTIONS.md:27-40` required it for every family). Mechanical fix landed `bffa01b`. Vault L1 has 0/3 — code wired (`vault_models.py`, `vault_graph.py`, `vault_diff.py`, `commander_cli.py:786`) but schema still `scaffold-only`, no smoke scenario, no transcript. Pattern: every status-bump PR description must explicitly check all 3 gates with cited evidence; partial bumps accumulate doc-vs-code drift that costs downstream worker cycles.
5125:431:   431	- 2026-04-27 [smoke][in-run-self-fix-during-live-proof] **A live-proof worker that hits real bugs during create→verify→destroy and self-fixes them inline with offline-test coverage is doing the right thing — but the LIVE-OK transcript should record the fixes as honest provenance, not hide them.** Sprint 7h-38 L1: vaultOneLogin live run hit 3 real bugs (provider sync-spinner contamination of in-proc `ls`/`get` JSON, vault empty-manifest stem coupling for delete-detection, sandbox cleanup using soft-delete instead of marker-guarded `rm --force`); worker self-fixed each + added offline tests, then re-ran the live cycle clean. The sanitized transcript's `notes` field captured the fixes. Rule: prompt allows ONE in-run minimal fix attempt; > 1 attempt → declare LIVE-FAIL, revert any partial fix, and let parent decide. Future template improvement: split "live-proof" (clean run, no fixes) from "live-debug" (run + fix + re-run + commit fix-with-transcript) into two slice templates so the LIVE-OK transcript stays clean of in-run bug notes when the goal is pure proof.
5126:445:   445	- 2026-04-27 [codex-prompts][sprint-templates-vs-prefabs] **`tasks/PREFAB_*.md` is full bodies for repeated workloads; `templates/SPRINT_*.md` is skeletons with `${VAR}` placeholders for the per-sprint slice patterns the orchestrator hand-writes ~5x per sprint. Three templates land 7h-40 V5c: offline-write-feature, readonly-memo, live-proof.** Each ends with an LESSONS-derived anti-patterns section that the orchestrator updates whenever a new violation surfaces (drift policy: snippet edits go through LESSONS.md first, then the template, with version: bump). Pattern: when a sprint prompt structure repeats >3 times, extract the skeleton to a `templates/SPRINT_*.md` and cite origin sprints in the header.
